                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-date&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;comment-link&quot; href=&quot;#comment26603544_1568150&quot;&gt;&lt;span title=&quot;2013-08-10 09:49:56Z, License: CC BY-SA 3.0&quot; class=&quot;relativetime-clean&quot;&gt;Aug 10, 2013 at 9:49&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@TimoHuovinen How is that any different than a user in Java assuming that &lt;code&gt;obj.setAttr(&apos;foo&apos;)&lt;/code&gt; &quot;just sets the variable without anything else happening&quot;? If it&apos;s a public methods, then it&apos;s a public method. If you use it to achieve some side-effect, and it is public, then you had better be able to count on everything working &lt;i&gt;as if only that intended side effect happened&lt;/i&gt; (with &lt;i&gt;all&lt;/i&gt; other implementation details and other side effects, resource use, whatever, hidden from the user&apos;s concerns). This is absolutely no different with Python. Python&apos;s syntax to achieve the effect is just simpler.&lt;/span&gt;

